sentences: Jack Arthur Walrath (born May 5, 1946) is an American post-bop jazz trumpeter and musical arranger known for his work with Ray Charles, Gary Peacock, Charles Mingus, and Glenn Ferris, among others.
He began playing the trumpet at the age of nine in 1955 while living in the small town of Edgar, Montana.
In 1969 Walrath relocated to the West Coast and found work in Los Angeles's jazz scene.
In 1970 Walrath relocated to New York City.
For a year and a half he was a columnist of the International Musician and Recording World, which had its US department there.
Walrath spent the next several years working with mainstream and Latin jazz bands.
With Mingus he recorded Changes One and Changes Two, both for Atlantic Records in 1974.
